  Patient: DODSON,LOURESTA L
Specimen #:  S00-2486
Accessioned: 08/07/00
  Pathologist: ALAAELDEEN M. ELSAYED, Lt Col, USAF, MC, FS
                                    **ADDENDUM**

  SPECIMEN:
    RIGHT BREAST MASS

  CLINICAL DIAGNOSIS AND HISTORY:
    41 YO FEMALE  W/ RIGHT BREAST MASS FOR 10 YEARS. LAST YEAR GETTING
LARGER SLOWLY.

  PRE-OPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:
    RIGHT BREAST MASS

  POST-OPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:
    Post-operative Diagnosis: RIGHT BREAST MASS

  GROSS DESCRIPTION:
    Received in formalin, labeled with patient's name, identification #
and "1 right breast mass" and consists of a segment of breast/soft tissue
measuring approximately 4.5 x 3.2 x 2.3 cm in the longest dimensions and
weighing 11.3 grams.  The specimen is inked and serially vertically
sectioned revealing a greyish white fibrous-like cut surface alternating
with yellowish adipose-like areas.  Representative sections are submitted
in two cassettes labeled A1 and A2.

  FINAL DIAGNOSIS:
    RIGHT BREAST, EXCISIONAL BIOPSY OF "MASS":
        -  BENIGN BREAST TISSUE WITH PERIDUCTAL FIBROSIS, DUCT ECTASIA,
           BENIGN INTRADUCTAL PAPILLOMA, AND ATYPICAL INTRADUCTAL
HYPERPLASIA.
 COMMENT:
    Case forwarded to the Armed Forces Institute of Pathology Department
of Breast and Gynecologic Pathology.

    REFERRAL:
    AFIP


    lcd/08/09/00
** Report Electronically Signed **
ALAAELDEEN M. ELSAYED, Lt Col, USAF, MC, FS


  ADDENDUM:
    ** SIGNED OUT 09/01/00 **
    This addendum is issued to reflect the results of expert consultation
in AFIP report #2742601 SEQ 00 and is entered into the electronic report
by the Pathology Department  transcriptionist. A copy of the AFIP report
is forwarded to the patient's attending physician and medical records.
    S00-2486 RIGHT BREAST, BIOPSY: FOCAL DUCTAL INTRAEPITHELIAL NEOPLASIA,
                                   GRADE 1B (DIN 1B) (ATYPICAL INTRADUCTAL
                                   HYPERPLASIA),FLAT AND CRIBRIFORM TYPES,
                                   SEE COMMENT.
                                 : FIBROCYSTIC CHANGES WITH MICROCYSTS AND
                                   STROMAL FIBROSIS.
                                 : SCLEROSING ADENOSIS, MILD.
                                 : PSEUDOANGIOMATOUS STROMAL HYPERPLASIA
                                   (PASH), MILD.

    THIS CASE WAS REVIEWED IN STAFF CONFERENCE. THE STAFF ESSENTIALLY
CONCURS WITH YOUR INTERPRETATIONS BUT PREFERS THE ABOVE TERMINOLOGY.  A
COPY OF THE RECENTLY PROPOSED CLASSIFICATION SCHEME FOR INTRADUCTAL
EPITHELIAL PROLIFERATIONS WITH COMPARISON TO CONVENTIONAL TERMINOLOGY IS
INCLUDED FOR YOUR REFERENCE.

    ALTHOUGH PSEUDOANGIOMATOUS STROMAL HYPERPLASIA (PASH) MAY BE A CAUSE
OF A CLINICAL BREAST MASS, FOLLOW UP OF ANY PERSISTENT/RESIDUAL BREAST
MASS IS SUGGESTED, AS CLINICALLY APPROPRIATE.

    A SMALL, DETACHED INTRADUCTAL EPITHELIAL FRAGMENT WITH PROMINENT
ELECTROCAUTERY ARTIFACT IS NOTED WITHIN THE LUMEN OF A DUCT (SLIDE A1);
THIS FINDING IS NON-DIAGNOSTIC, BUT A TINY FRAGMENT OF A PAPILLARY LESION
CAN NOT BE COMPLETELY RULED OUT.

    SIGNED BY: KRIS M. SHEKITKA, M.D.

    khb/09/01/00
** Addendum Electronically Signed **
ALAAELDEEN M. ELSAYED, Lt  Col, USAF, MC, FS

    88305 ; 88305 ; SP:LEVEL IV (88305)
